<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sequences-and-series-of-functions"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Sequences and Series of Functions</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Power series, Fourier series, and many approximation procedures are
      built from sequences of functions. The basic question is simple: if
      each function in the sequence is well behaved, what can be said about
      the limit? Pointwise convergence is often too weak, so the right notion
      for analysis is usually uniform convergence.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    Let <m>S \subseteq \R</m>, and let <m>(f_n)</m> be a sequence of
    functions from <m>S</m> to <m>\R</m>. We say that <m>f_n</m> converges
    <term>pointwise</term><idx><h>convergence</h><h>pointwise</h></idx> on
    <m>S</m> to a function <m>f \colon S \to \R</m> if for every
    <m>x \in S</m> the numerical sequence <m>(f_n(x))</m> converges to
    <m>f(x)</m>.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-pointwise-limit-xn">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f_n(x)=x^n</m> on <m>[0,1]</m>. Then <m>f_n(x)\to 0</m> for
        every <m>x \in [0,1)</m>, while <m>f_n(1)=1</m> for every <m>n</m>.
        Thus the pointwise limit is
        <md>
          f(x)=\begin{cases}
            0 &amp; \text{if } 0 \le x \lt 1,\\
            1 &amp; \text{if } x=1.
          \end{cases}
        </md>
        Each <m>f_n</m> is a polynomial, but the limit is not continuous at
        <m>1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    Pointwise convergence looks at one input <m>x</m> at a time. The index
    <m>N</m> that makes <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)|</m> small is allowed to depend on
    <m>x</m>. Uniform convergence removes that dependence.
  </p>

  <p>
    We say that <m>f_n</m> converges <term>uniformly</term>
    <idx><h>convergence</h><h>uniform</h></idx> on <m>S</m> to <m>f</m> if
    for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there
    exists <m>N \in \N</m> such that
    <md>
      |f_n(x)-f(x)| \lt \varepsilon
      \qquad \text{for all } n \ge N \text{ and all } x \in S.
    </md>
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-uniform-implies-pointwise-functions">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Uniform convergence implies pointwise convergence.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Fix <m>x \in S</m>. If <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>S</m>, then
        for every <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>N</m> such that
        <m>|f_n(y)-f(y)| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all <m>y \in S</m> and all
        <m>n \ge N</m>. In particular, the same inequality holds when
        <m>y=x</m>. Therefore <m>f_n(x)\to f(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <example xml:id="eg-pointwise-not-uniform-xn">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The convergence in <xref ref="eg-pointwise-limit-xn"/> is not uniform
        on <m>[0,1]</m>. Let <m>f</m> be the pointwise limit. For
        <m>x_n=n/(n+1)</m> we have <m>x_n \in [0,1)</m>, so <m>f(x_n)=0</m>,
        while
        <md>
          f_n(x_n)=\left(\frac{n}{n+1}\right)^n \to e^{-1}.
        </md>
        Hence <m>|f_n(x_n)-f(x_n)|</m> does not tend to <m>0</m>. Therefore
        <m>f_n</m> cannot converge uniformly to <m>f</m> on <m>[0,1]</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    If <m>f \colon S \to \R</m> is bounded, its
    <term>supremum norm</term><idx><h>norm</h><h>supremum</h></idx> on
    <m>S</m> is
    <md>
      \|f\|_S := \sup\{|f(x)| : x \in S\}.
    </md>
    When the set <m>S</m> is understood, we simply write <m>\|f\|</m>.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-uniform-convergence-supnorm">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>f_n</m> and <m>f</m> are bounded on <m>S</m> for every
        <m>n</m>. Then <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>S</m> if and only if
        <md>
          \|f_n-f\|_S \to 0.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>S</m>, then for every
        <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>N</m> such that
        <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)| \lt \varepsilon</m> for all <m>x \in S</m> and all
        <m>n \ge N</m>. Taking the supremum over <m>x</m> gives
        <m>\|f_n-f\|_S \le \varepsilon</m> for <m>n \ge N</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Conversely, if <m>\|f_n-f\|_S \to 0</m>, then for every
        <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>N</m> such that
        <m>\|f_n-f\|_S \lt \varepsilon</m> whenever <m>n \ge N</m>. Hence
        <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)| \le \|f_n-f\|_S \lt \varepsilon</m> for every
        <m>x \in S</m>, which is exactly uniform convergence.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-uniform-cauchy-criterion-functions">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>(f_n)</m> be a sequence of functions on <m>S</m>. Then
        <m>(f_n)</m> converges uniformly on <m>S</m> if and only if for every
        <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> there exists <m>N</m> such that
        <md>
          |f_m(x)-f_n(x)| \lt \varepsilon
          \qquad \text{for all } m,n \ge N \text{ and all } x \in S.
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        If <m>f_n \to f</m> uniformly on <m>S</m>, then for every
        <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m> we may choose <m>N</m> so that
        <m>|f_n(x)-f(x)| \lt \varepsilon/2</m> for all <m>x \in S</m> and all
        <m>n \ge N</m>. Therefore, whenever <m>m,n \ge N</m>,
        <md>
          |f_m(x)-f_n(x)|
          \le
          |f_m(x)-f(x)|+|f_n(x)-f(x)|
          \lt
          \varepsilon
        </md>
        for all <m>x \in S</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Conversely, suppose the displayed condition holds. Fix
        <m>x \in S</m>. Then <m>(f_n(x))</m> is a Cauchy sequence in
        <m>\R</m>, so it converges by completeness. Define
        <m>f(x)=\lim_{n\to\infty} f_n(x)</m>. Now let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>
        and choose <m>N</m> as in the hypothesis. For <m>n \ge N</m> and
        fixed <m>x \in S</m>, the inequality
        <m>|f_m(x)-f_n(x)| \lt \varepsilon</m> holds for all <m>m \ge N</m>.
        Letting <m>m \to \infty</m> gives
        <m>|f(x)-f_n(x)| \le \varepsilon</m>. Since this estimate is valid for
        every <m>x \in S</m>, the convergence is uniform.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    A <term>series of functions</term><idx><h>series</h><h>of functions</h></idx>
    <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty f_n</m> on <m>S</m> is studied through its partial
    sums
    <md>
      s_N(x)=\sum_{n=0}^N f_n(x).
    </md>
    We say that the series converges pointwise or uniformly according as the
    sequence <m>(s_N)</m> does.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-weierstrass-m-test-functions">
    <title>Weierstrass M-Test</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>(f_n)</m> be a sequence of functions on <m>S</m>. Suppose
        there are numbers <m>M_n \ge 0</m> such that
        <md>
          |f_n(x)| \le M_n
          \qquad \text{for all } x \in S \text{ and all } n,
        </md>
        and suppose that the numerical series <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty M_n</m>
        converges. Then the series <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty f_n</m> converges
        absolutely and uniformly on <m>S</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>s_N(x)=\sum_{n=0}^N f_n(x)</m>. Since
        <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty M_n</m> converges, its tails tend to <m>0</m>.
        Thus, given <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>, there exists <m>N</m> such that
        for all <m>m \gt n \ge N</m>,
        <md>
          \sum_{k=n+1}^m M_k \lt \varepsilon.
        </md>
        Hence for every <m>x \in S</m>,
        <md>
          |s_m(x)-s_n(x)|
          \le
          \sum_{k=n+1}^m |f_k(x)|
          \le
          \sum_{k=n+1}^m M_k
          \lt
          \varepsilon.
        </md>
        By <xref ref="prop-uniform-cauchy-criterion-functions"/>, the partial
        sums converge uniformly on <m>S</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For each fixed <m>x \in S</m>, the estimate
        <m>|f_n(x)| \le M_n</m> also shows that the numerical series
        <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty |f_n(x)|</m> converges by comparison. Therefore
        the convergence is absolute at every point.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-geometric-series-uniform-on-closed-subinterval">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>0 \lt r \lt 1</m>. On the interval <m>[-r,r]</m> we have
        <m>|x^n| \le r^n</m>, and the geometric series
        <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty r^n</m> converges. Therefore
        <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n</m> converges uniformly on <m>[-r,r]</m> by
        the Weierstrass M-test.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-power-series-uniform-on-compact-subintervals">
    <title>Uniform Convergence on Closed Subintervals</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the power series
        <md>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n(x-x_0)^n
        </md>
        has radius of convergence <m>R \gt 0</m>. Then for every
        <m>r</m> with <m>0 \lt r \lt R</m>, the series converges absolutely
        and uniformly on the closed interval <m>[x_0-r,x_0+r]</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>L=\limsup |a_n|^{1/n}=1/R</m>. Choose a number <m>\rho</m>
        such that
        <md>
          L \lt \rho \lt \frac{1}{r}.
        </md>
        By the definition of <m>\limsup</m>, there exists <m>N</m> such that
        <m>|a_n|^{1/n} \le \rho</m> for every <m>n \ge N</m>, and hence
        <m>|a_n| \le \rho^n</m> for all such <m>n</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>|x-x_0| \le r</m> and <m>n \ge N</m>, then
        <md>
          |a_n(x-x_0)^n|
          \le
          \rho^n r^n
          =
          (\rho r)^n.
        </md>
        Since <m>\rho r \lt 1</m>, the geometric series
        <m>\sum_{n=N}^\infty (\rho r)^n</m> converges. For the finitely many
        indices <m>n \lt N</m>, set <m>M_n=|a_n|r^n</m>. Then
        <m>|a_n(x-x_0)^n| \le M_n</m> for every <m>x \in [x_0-r,x_0+r]</m>
        and every <m>n</m>, and the numerical series <m>\sum M_n</m>
        converges. The Weierstrass M-test now gives absolute and uniform
        convergence on the stated interval.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-geometric-series-not-uniform-on-open-interval">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The geometric series
        <md>
          \sum_{n=0}^\infty x^n
        </md>
        converges to <m>1/(1-x)</m> on <m>(-1,1)</m>, but the convergence is
        not uniform on that open interval. Indeed, if
        <m>s_N(x)=1+x+\dots+x^N</m>, then
        <md>
          \frac{1}{1-x}-s_N(x)=\frac{x^{N+1}}{1-x}.
        </md>
        For each fixed <m>N</m>, the right-hand side becomes arbitrarily large
        as <m>x \to 1^-</m>. Hence <m>s_N</m> cannot converge uniformly to
        <m>1/(1-x)</m> on <m>(-1,1)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</section>
